# {{APP_NAME}}

A multi-runtime Electron desktop app for local-LLM chat. Out of the box it
handles three model file formats with three different inference backends:

| Format | Runtime | Where it runs | Grammar / GBNF |
|---|---|---|---|
| `.gguf` | bundled `llama-server.exe` | main-process subprocess | yes (sampling-time) |
| `.task` | `@mediapipe/tasks-genai` | renderer (WebAssembly) | no (prompt fallback) |
| `.litertlm` | (recognized, not yet usable) | — | — |

Powered by [`machineai-activation`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/machineai-activation)
+ [`machineai-activation-ui`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/machineai-activation-ui).

## Why this template doesn't use `node-llama-cpp`

Most Electron + llama.cpp tutorials reach for `node-llama-cpp`. That works
for the first commit, but it bakes a staleness defect into every downstream
app: the npm package ships a frozen llama.cpp build, and when a new model
architecture lands upstream (Gemma 4, the next Llama, ...) every app
breaks until npm catches up.

This template avoids the trap by vendoring llama.cpp's official
[GitHub-published `llama-server`](https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/releases)
binary at build time and spawning it as a subprocess. The OpenAI-compatible
HTTP+SSE surface is stable across llama.cpp versions, so updating to a
newer build is just `npm run fetch:llama` — no source compile, no native
rebuild step, no waiting for someone to publish a new npm release.

## Why a multi-format picker, not a hard-coded cartridge

Cartridge ids are fine for a fixed-model demo. Real users want to point at
GGUFs they already have on disk (LM Studio, Ollama, text-gen-webui all
share the same files). The template's first-run flow is a file picker that
remembers the path in `<userData>/config.json`, plus a "switch model"
button in the chat UI. Picker accepts `.gguf`, `.task`, and `.litertlm`;
the renderer's `runtimeSelector.ts` routes each to the right backend.

## Prerequisites

- Node 20+.
- Internet on first build (the fetch script downloads ~16 MB of llama.cpp
  binaries into `vendor/llama-cpp/`). Subsequent builds reuse the cache.
- Windows x64 today. Adding macOS/Linux is small: extend the asset name
  pattern in `scripts/fetch-llama-cpp.js` and the binary path in
  `electron/llamaServerRuntime.ts`.

## Get started

```bash
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} install
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run fetch:llama
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run dev
```

`dev` runs Vite (renderer dev server on :5173), `tsc --watch` for the main
process, and Electron — all concurrently. Hot-reload works for the
renderer; main-process changes restart Electron.

### Production build + installer

```bash
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run build      # fetch:llama + typecheck + bundle + vite
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run package    # NSIS installer at release/*.exe
```

`build` re-runs `fetch:llama` first so a fresh package always ships the
latest llama.cpp.

## Architecture

```
┌─ main process ─────────────────────────────────┐
│  electron/main.ts                              │
│    • app-model:// custom protocol              │
│    • config.json: { modelFilePath }            │
│    • IPC handlers (machine, config, memory…)   │
│    ↓                                           │
│  llamaServerRuntime.ts                         │
│    spawn ── llama-server.exe ── HTTP/SSE       │
│    (vendor/llama-cpp/win-x64/)                 │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
       ↕ IPC (contextBridge: window.machine, .config)
┌─ renderer ─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  src/App.tsx                                   │
│    runtimeSelector picks per file extension    │
│  src/lib/ipcRuntime.ts        (.gguf path)     │
│  src/lib/mediaPipeRuntime.ts  (.task path)     │
│    LlmInference + WebAssembly                  │
│    loads model via app-model:// URL            │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

The renderer never knows which backend is active. Both runtimes implement
the same `ActivationRuntime` interface, and both are wrapped in a
`Machine` via `createMachine({ runtimes })`. Hooks like `useMachineModel`,
`streamText`, `generateObject` work identically on either path — except
for `generateObject`'s GBNF-at-sampling-time guarantee, which only fires
on the `.gguf` (llama-server) path. On `.task` it falls back to the
prompt-and-retry shape.

## Updating llama.cpp

```bash
rm -rf vendor/llama-cpp
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run fetch:llama
```

Always pulls `releases/latest`. Re-run before the next `npm run package`.

## Updating MediaPipe (`.task` runtime)

```bash
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} install @mediapipe/tasks-genai@latest
{{PACKAGE_MANAGER}} run build
```

The Vite plugin in `vite.config.ts` re-copies the WASM files into the
renderer bundle on every build, so just bumping the npm package is
enough.

## Why no `.litertlm`?

Google's LiteRT-LM CLI shipped a Windows binary in v0.11.0 (May 2026), but:

1. The Windows release artifact is missing required runtime DLLs and exits
   with `STATUS_DLL_NOT_FOUND` on startup — verified, not yet fixed
   upstream.
2. The CLI is single-shot `--prompt="…"` only — no daemon mode, no
   streaming, no grammar. Not embeddable as a chat backend.

When upstream ships a complete release with a daemon mode, adding it as a
third runtime is straightforward (mirror `llamaServerRuntime.ts`'s
spawn-and-HTTP pattern). For now, the picker accepts `.litertlm` so users
who pick one get a clear explanatory notice instead of a confusing
"runtime missing" error.

